 zebra mimic the ripples in windblown sand. That’s because, as Patterns in Nature shows, at the most basic level these patterns can often be described using the same mathematical and physical principles: there is a surprising underlying unity in the kaleidoscope of the natural world. Richly illustrated with 250 color photographs and anchored by accessible and insightful chapters by esteemed science writer Philip Ball, Patterns in Nature reveals the organization at work in vast and ancient forests, powerful rivers, massing clouds, and coastlines carved out by the sea. By exploring similarities such as those between a snail shell and the swirling stars of a galaxy, or the branches of a tree and those of a river network, this spectacular visual tour conveys the wonder, beauty, and richness of natural pattern formation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aGeometry in nature. 0aNature. 0aPattern formation (Biology) 0aPattern formation (Biology). 0aPattern formation (Physical sciences) 0aPattern formation (Physical sciences). 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh  anature, natural world, patterns, diversity, complexity, species, hexagon, honeycomb, fractals, spiral, seashell, leaves, chaos, biology, technology, architecture, art, artistic, spirals, symmetry, waves, dunes, bubbles, foam, ocean, landscape, desert, wildlife, tiling, spots, stripes, physical science, scientific, geometry, math, mathematics, academic, scholarly, educational, textbook, popular culture, photographs, illustrated.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226332567423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226332567/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-